A $y$-intercept is a point on the graph that lies on the $y$-axis, so $x = 0$.  Hence, the number $y$-intercepts corresponds to the number of real solutions of the quadratic equation $-y^2 + 4y - 4$.  The discriminant of this quadratic equation is $4^2 - 4 \cdot (-1) \cdot (-4) = 0$, so the quadratic has exactly one real root.  (We can also see this by writing $-y^2 + 4y - 4 = -(y - 2)^2$.)  Therefore, the number of $y$-intercepts is ${1}$.

